Binary Search (Java)
Problem Statement

Given a sorted array of integers nums and a target value target, return the index of target if it exists.
If not found, return -1.

Example Problem
Input: nums = [1, 3, 5, 7, 9], target = 7
Output: 3
Explanation: 7 is present at index 3.

Key Point

ðŸ‘‰ Binary Search works ONLY on sorted arrays

Algorithm (Binary Search)
Step-by-step

Initialize two pointers:

low = 0

high = nums.length - 1

While low <= high:

Find mid = (low + high) / 2

Compare:

If nums[mid] == target â†’ return mid

If nums[mid] < target â†’ move right â†’ low = mid + 1

If nums[mid] > target â†’ move left â†’ high = mid - 1

If not found â†’ return -1

Java Code
public class BinarySearch {

    public static int binarySearch(int[] nums, int target) {
        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;

        while (low <= high) {
            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] == target)
                return mid;
            else if (nums[mid] < target)
                low = mid + 1;
            else
                high = mid - 1;
        }

        return -1; // element not found
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] nums = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9};
        int target = 7;

        int result = binarySearch(nums, target);
        System.out.println("Index of target: " + result); // Output: 3
    }
}

Code Explanation

low â†’ starting index

high â†’ ending index

mid â†’ middle element

We reduce half of the array each time, making it fast.

Dry Run (Example)
nums = [1,3,5,7,9], target = 7

low=0, high=4
mid=2 â†’ nums[2]=5 < 7 â†’ low=3

low=3, high=4
mid=3 â†’ nums[3]=7 == target â†’ return 3

Test Case
Input: nums = [2,4,6,8,10], target = 5
Output: -1
Explanation: 5 is not present in the array.

Complexity Analysis

Time Complexity: O(log n)

Space Complexity: O(1)
